{"title": "Pamphilia to Amphilanthus: 2",
"body": ["Love like a jugler, comes to play his prise,", "And all minds draw his wonders to admire,", "To see how cuningly hee, wanting eyes,", "Can yett deseave the best sight of desire:", "The wanton child, how hee can faine his fire", "So pretely, as none sees his disguise!", "How finely doe his tricks, while wee fooles hire", "The badge, and office of his tirannies,", "For in the end, such jugling hee doth make", "As hee our harts, in stead of eyes doth take", "For men can only by theyr slieghts abuse", "The sight with nimble, and delightful skill;", "Butt if hee play, his gaine is our lost will:", "Yett childlike, wee can nott his sports refuse."],
