{"title": "Sonnet 18: Shall I compare thee to a summer\u2019s day?",
"body": ["Shall I compare thee to a summer\u2019s day?", "Thou art more lovely and more temperate:", "Rough winds do shake the darling buds of May,", "And summer\u2019s lease hath all too short a date;", "Sometime too hot the eye of heaven shines,", "And often is his gold complexion dimm'd;", "And every fair from fair sometime declines,", "By chance or nature\u2019s changing course untrimm'd;", "But thy eternal summer shall not fade,", "Nor lose possession of that fair thou ow\u2019st;", "Nor shall death brag thou wander\u2019st in his shade,", "When in eternal lines to time thou grow\u2019st:", "So long as men can breathe or eyes can see,", "So long lives this, and this gives life to thee."],
